═══════════════════════════════════════════════
REWRITE INSTRUCTIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════

VOICE: Direct, energetic, credible.
Not corporate. Not cautious. Not "wellness-speak."
Write like a confident brand that knows its product works.

META TITLE (50-60 chars):
- Primary keyword first
- Brand name after pipe
- Must reflect what the product actually does
- Example structure: "Keyword Descriptor | Protein Works"

H1 (max 8 words):
- Lead with customer outcome not product name
- The visitor must understand the product in 3 seconds
- No health claims
- Bad: "All In A.I. Greens Superfood Formula"
- Good: "The Greens Powder You'll Actually Drink Daily"

SUB-HEADLINE (max 20 words):
- Answer the single biggest purchase objection immediately
- For this product that objection is TASTE
- Reference specific review evidence about taste if available
- Do not make efficacy claims

BENEFIT HIGHLIGHTS (5-7 bullets):
- Lead with outcome the customer cares about
- Follow with the ingredient that delivers it
- End with the authorised claim in plain language
- Format: [Outcome] — [Ingredient] — [Authorised claim]
- Bad: "Supports immunity with Vitamin C"
- Good: "Stay sharp through winter — Vitamin C and Zinc contribute to the normal function of your immune system"
- Every compliance-sensitive bullet ends with [HUMAN REVIEW REQUIRED]

FAQ — OBJECTION HANDLING (3-5 Q&A pairs):
Address these specific objections in this order:
1. "Does it actually taste good?"
   Use ONLY review snippets verbatim from the page data. If no taste reviews exist, skip this Q.
2. "Is the price worth it vs cheaper alternatives?"
   Focus on ingredient quality, formulation depth, and brand credibility — NOT the price itself.
   Do NOT mention or quote the price. Do NOT compare prices to competitors.
   Use ONLY ingredient names and quality points that appear in the scraped data.
   DO NOT invent or calculate: gram amounts, serving counts, price-per-serving, bag weights,
   or any number not explicitly stated in the source.
3. "Will I actually notice a difference?"
   Use authorised claims only — no efficacy promises
4. "Can I cancel if I subscribe?"
   Only include if subscription data is in the page data

TRUST SIGNAL BLOCK (2-3 sentences):
- Use ONLY claims verifiable from the page data
- Do not invent review counts, certifications, or awards not in the scraped data
- If award badges are in image_descriptions — use them
- If review count is in the data — use it
- Format: specific claim + specific evidence

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
ANTI-HALLUCINATION RULES — NON-NEGOTIABLE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════

NEVER invent or calculate specific numbers. This includes:
- The product price (e.g. "£50", "£39.99") — only use the exact price from the source data
- Weight or volume amounts (e.g. "15g", "960g", "500ml")
- Serving counts (e.g. "64 servings", "30 servings")
- Derived prices (e.g. "£0.46 per serving" — only use if price_per_serving is in the data)
- Specific nutrient doses (e.g. "1000mg Vitamin C") unless stated verbatim in the source
- Ingredient counts (e.g. "69 ingredients") unless stated verbatim in the source
- Percentages, rankings, or statistics not present in the scraped content

If a specific number is not in the source JSON, DO NOT write it. Either omit the detail or
write [DATA UNVERIFIED — check source] in its place.

